{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18230"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18230"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.04,0.54,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77475"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10944"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18230"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62987"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10131"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25436"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77475"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESecondary hyperparathyroidism is a condition characterised by increased production of parathyroid hormone (PTH) in response to low calcium levels in the blood.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common cause of increased parathyroid hormone production in secondary hyperparathyroidism associated with hypocalcaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vitamin D deficiency","Crohn\u0027s disease","Chronic kidney disease","Peptic ulcer","Systemic lupus erythematosus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of increased parathyroid hormone production in secondary hyperparathyroidism is \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E. Impaired phosphate excretion and reduced activation of vitamin D results in hypocalcaemia. This stimulates the parathyroid glands to produce more parathyroid hormone in an attempt to increase calcium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E - While it can contribute to secondary hyperparathyroidism, it is not the most common cause\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E - This condition can lead to malabsorption but is not a primary cause of secondary hyperparathyroidism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E - This condition is unrelated to parathyroid hormone production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E - This autoimmune disease does not directly cause secondary hyperparathyroidism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary hyperparathyroidism is often caused by chronic kidney disease due to impaired phosphate excretion and reduced vitamin D activation.","Chronic kidney disease leads to hypocalcaemia, which stimulates increased parathyroid hormone production.","Vitamin D deficiency can also contribute to secondary hyperparathyroidism by reducing calcium absorption."],"references":["de Francisco AL. Secondary hyperparathyroidism: review of the disease and its treatment. Clin Ther. 2004 Dec;26(12):1976-93. doi: 10.1016/j.clinthera.2004.12.011. PMID: 15823762.","Habas E Sr, Eledrisi M, Khan F, Elzouki AY. Secondary Hyperparathyroidism in Chronic Kidney Disease: Pathophysiology and Management. Cureus. 2021 Jul 14;13(7):e16388. doi: 10.7759/cureus.16388. PMID: 34408941; PMCID: PMC8362860.","Yuen NK, Ananthakrishnan S, Campbell MJ. Hyperparathyroidism of Renal Disease. Perm J. 2016 Summer;20(3):15-127. doi: 10.7812/TPP/15-127. Epub 2016 Jul 22. PMID: 27479950; PMCID: PMC4991918.","Muppidi V, Meegada SR, Rehman A. Secondary Hyperparathyroidism. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557822/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62987"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18230"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62987"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T08:54:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T08:55:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10944"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77475"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"